calEvent.description:
This March, The National Ballet of Canada performs George Balanchine’s neoclassical masterpiece Apollo onstage with Night and The Sea Above, Sky Below and Paquita.

Apollo is considered one of ballet’s masterpieces. It established a new aesthetic that brought the language of classical ballet into a modern context and is considered an iconic role for the male dancer. Following Apollo, is the company premiere of Night by Julia Adam. This work is a glorious dreamscape inspired by the paintings of Marc Chagall, set to music by Gustav Mahler. Also, on the programme is The Sea Above, The Sky Below, an intricate pas de trois by Robert Binet. Closing the the programme is Associate Artistic Director Christopher Stowell’s dazzling new adaptation of Paquita, based on the famous 1881 version by Marius Petipa. An unabashed celebration of classical technique, Paquita is a great showcase for the dancers, full of colour and panache.

In the beginning there was an earthquake, then a massive wave took everything.
